61
00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:42.680
trial that was designed to test the effectiveness of two

62
00:03:42.740 --> 00:03:46.240
mailed outreach interventions to increase colorectal cancer

63
00:03:46.360 --> 00:03:48.720
screening in community health settings.

64
00:03:49.140 --> 00:03:51.280
And I want to acknowledge our

65
00:03:52.080 --> 00:03:55.980
large multidisciplinary team, who you can see named here,

66
00:03:56.760 --> 00:04:00.609
as well as the support of our participating sites, as well as our

67
00:04:00.720 --> 00:04:02.060
funder, Stand Up To Cancer.

68
00:04:03.320 --> 00:04:05.200
First, I want to give you a little bit of background.

69
00:04:05.840 --> 00:04:09.760
In the United States, community health centers, or CHCs, provide

70
00:04:09.800 --> 00:04:13.049
primary care services to nearly 34 million

71
00:04:13.100 --> 00:04:16.899
people, most of whom are low income, uninsured, or

72
00:04:16.959 --> 00:04:20.680
from racial, ethnic minority populations.

73
00:04:20.760 --> 00:04:24.660
This is currently about 10% of the US population, and

74
00:04:24.700 --> 00:04:28.560
unfortunately, as more people lose insurance, it is anticipated that

75
00:04:28.600 --> 00:04:32.560
this population will grow. Although colorectal cancer, or

76
00:04:32.740 --> 00:04:36.530
CRC, remember that, that's an important distinction, CRC

77
00:04:36.560 --> 00:04:40.040
versus CHC, is the second leading cause of

78
00:04:40.100 --> 00:04:43.920
cancer-related mortality in the US, CRC screening is

79
00:04:43.980 --> 00:04:47.060
underutilized, especially in community health centers.

80
00:04:47.610 --> 00:04:51.040
Stool-based CRC screening modalities are commonly

81
00:04:51.160 --> 00:04:53.400
used in community health centers.

82
00:04:53.440 --> 00:04:57.240
However, effective stool-based screening requires follow-up

83
00:04:57.340 --> 00:05:00.540
of all abnormal results with a follow-up

84
00:05:00.620 --> 00:05:04.060
colonoscopy, and these rates in community health

85
00:05:04.100 --> 00:05:06.420
centers are also particularly low.

86
00:05:08.100 --> 00:05:11.240
This slide just gives you a little bit of sense of where

87
00:05:11.820 --> 00:05:14.730
colorectal cancer screening rates are in the United States.

88
00:05:15.460 --> 00:05:19.340
So about 60%, which is what this dotted blue line

89
00:05:20.100 --> 00:05:20.920
represents.

90
00:05:21.840 --> 00:05:22.300
And

91
00:05:23.160 --> 00:05:26.960
you can see from the bar graph that community health centers have

92
00:05:27.040 --> 00:05:30.840
continued to perform well below the national screening

93
00:05:30.920 --> 00:05:34.420
rate over the past 10 years, recently just over

94
00:05:34.580 --> 00:05:35.280
40%.

95
00:05:36.080 --> 00:05:39.850
Additionally, follow-up colonoscopy rates after an abnormal stool-based

96
00:05:39.960 --> 00:05:43.900
test result are also very low in community health centers, and published

97
00:05:43.940 --> 00:05:47.320
reports suggest that only 18% to

98
00:05:47.500 --> 00:05:51.340
62% of people with an abnormal stool result

99
00:05:51.660 --> 00:05:53.500
will get a follow-up colonoscopy.

100
00:05:53.760 --> 00:05:56.060
So, very discouraging

101
00:05:56.080 --> 00:05:59.750
results.To just to focus on the importance of this

102
00:05:59.780 --> 00:06:03.660
point, community health centers often use stool-based tests

103
00:06:03.700 --> 00:06:06.990
to screen for colorectal cancer. Stool-based tests are

104
00:06:07.020 --> 00:06:09.540
inexpensive and readily available.

105
00:06:09.810 --> 00:06:12.980
Stool-based CRC screening modalities include fecal

106
00:06:13.060 --> 00:06:16.920
immunochemical testing or FIT and FIT-DNA, which

107
00:06:16.980 --> 00:06:19.800
is currently sold under the brand name of Cologuard.

108
00:06:20.500 --> 00:06:23.780
Both can be mailed, allowing for population outreach.

109
00:06:24.480 --> 00:06:28.340
These stool-based screening modalities, again, are a two-step process that

110
00:06:28.360 --> 00:06:31.840
require follow-up colonoscopy if they're abnormal.

111
00:06:32.440 --> 00:06:36.140
Lack of colonoscopy after an abnormal stool-based test is

112
00:06:36.200 --> 00:06:39.249
associated with poor colorectal cancer outcomes,

113
00:06:39.760 --> 00:06:42.940
including increased colorectal cancer incidence,

114
00:06:43.300 --> 00:06:46.060
mortality, and late-stage diagnosis.

115
00:06:46.820 --> 00:06:50.540
So now on to our study, the Community Collaboration to

116
00:06:50.580 --> 00:06:54.410
Advance Racial Ethnic Equity in Colorectal Cancer Screening,

117
00:06:54.560 --> 00:06:57.060
or CARE-CCRS Study. It's a little bit of a mouthful.

118
00:06:57.840 --> 00:07:01.480
Compares two population outreach approaches to increase CRC

119
00:07:01.540 --> 00:07:05.500
screening uptake among screening-eligible adults who receive

120
00:07:05.580 --> 00:07:07.360
care in community health centers.

121
00:07:08.010 --> 00:07:11.600
And aim two was an exploratory aim where we

122
00:07:11.940 --> 00:07:15.680
sought to increase the completion of follow-up colonoscopy

123
00:07:15.780 --> 00:07:18.320
after an abnormal stool-based test result.

124
00:07:18.560 --> 00:07:22.320
So either one of the arms, FIT or FIT-DNA, through patient

125
00:07:22.380 --> 00:07:24.860
navigation to address barriers to follow-up.

126
00:07:25.800 --> 00:07:28.080
So now I'll move on to our design and methods.

127
00:07:28.600 --> 00:07:31.940
We conducted a pragmatic randomized trial in two U.S.

128
00:07:32.120 --> 00:07:36.020
regions that included four community health centers in Greater Boston

129
00:07:36.040 --> 00:07:38.520
and four community health centers in Los Angeles.

130
00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:42.760
In addition, we included a parallel non-randomized site

131
00:07:43.160 --> 00:07:46.140
at a tribal clinic in Rapid City, South Dakota.

132
00:07:47.110 --> 00:07:50.540
At each of these centers, we identified individuals aged

133
00:07:50.720 --> 00:07:54.440
45 to 75 who were due or overdue for

134
00:07:54.480 --> 00:07:58.160
colorectal cancer screening. We included patients with a

135
00:07:58.200 --> 00:08:01.980
recent primary care visit and those who had an English or

136
00:08:02.080 --> 00:08:03.740
Spanish language preference.

137
00:08:04.740 --> 00:08:08.639
We excluded people who did not have a physical mailing address or a

138
00:08:08.660 --> 00:08:12.590
phone number listed in the electronic health record because both of

139
00:08:12.620 --> 00:08:15.360
these were required for population outreach.

140
00:08:15.400 --> 00:08:19.260
We also excluded individuals with prior documentation of colorectal

141
00:08:19.320 --> 00:08:23.220
cancer, adenomatous polyps, Crohn's disease, or ulcerative

142
00:08:23.260 --> 00:08:27.140
colitis, as these individuals are at increased risk and are

143
00:08:27.200 --> 00:08:29.880
not typically appropriate for stool-based screening.

144
00:08:31.440 --> 00:08:35.100
We compared two competing strategies, FIT versus

145
00:08:35.201 --> 00:08:39.140
FIT-DNA. FIT is an annual test. We have listed

146
00:08:39.540 --> 00:08:42.220
some of the test characteristics here on the slide.

147
00:08:43.020 --> 00:08:46.920
FIT-DNA can be done every three years, reflecting its

148
00:08:46.940 --> 00:08:50.700
greater sensitivity for both colorectal cancer as well as

149
00:08:50.740 --> 00:08:54.360
advanced adenomas, which you can see down here in the comparison.

150
00:08:55.080 --> 00:08:57.940
But you'll also note that FIT-DNA has a somewhat lower

151
00:08:58.180 --> 00:08:59.940
specificity than FIT.

152
00:09:01.480 --> 00:09:05.300
Clinics were matched by region and size and then

153
00:09:05.400 --> 00:09:09.080
randomized to either the FIT or the FIT-DNA study arm.

154
00:09:09.760 --> 00:09:13.230
In the FIT arm, eligible patients were mailed an invitation

155
00:09:13.320 --> 00:09:16.560
letter to participate in the study, as well as an

156
00:09:16.640 --> 00:09:20.630
infographic highlighting the importance of colorectal cancer screening.

157
00:09:21.600 --> 00:09:25.440
Two weeks later, patients were mailed the CHC's

158
00:09:25.540 --> 00:09:29.320
usual brand of FIT kit, as well as a one-page

159
00:09:29.560 --> 00:09:33.190
English and Spanish instructional sheet pictured

160
00:09:33.240 --> 00:09:36.800
here that gave people instructions on how to

161
00:09:36.880 --> 00:09:40.420
complete the test. And you'll notice that this is largely an

162
00:09:40.480 --> 00:09:44.240
infographic with minimal words because we were really

163
00:09:44.600 --> 00:09:47.560
targeting people who may have a low literacy level.

164
00:09:47.820 --> 00:09:50.850
We also included prepaid postage and a mailer,

165
00:09:51.740 --> 00:09:55.280
and patients also had the option of dropping the FIT kits off at the

166
00:09:55.320 --> 00:09:55.860
clinics.

167
00:09:56.700 --> 00:10:00.620
And then finally, we sent up to three text messages to patients in the

168
00:10:00.680 --> 00:10:04.530
FIT arm. The first text message was sent before the FIT kit was

169
00:10:04.580 --> 00:10:08.480
mailed, letting the patient know that they would receive the kit in the mail

170
00:10:08.700 --> 00:10:12.260
soon. And then the second and third text messages were reminders to

171
00:10:12.320 --> 00:10:13.980
patients to complete the test.

172
00:10:16.320 --> 00:10:19.980
In the FIT-DNA arm, we also included the similar

173
00:10:20.080 --> 00:10:24.040
letter and the similar infographic with information about how

174
00:10:24.080 --> 00:10:25.140
to complete the kit.

175
00:10:26.160 --> 00:10:26.880
And then

176
00:10:27.800 --> 00:10:31.380
the FIT-DNA kit was mailed by Exact Sciences,

177
00:10:31.940 --> 00:10:35.300
who is the manufacturer of the FIT-DNA kit,

178
00:10:36.160 --> 00:10:39.760
and included materials on how to collect the sample with their

179
00:10:39.860 --> 00:10:43.180
standard instruction and how to complete the test.

180
00:10:43.240 --> 00:10:47.160
In the FIT-DNA arm, patients received the standard patient

181
00:10:47.260 --> 00:10:50.300
navigation program provided by Exact Sciences.

182
00:10:51.380 --> 00:10:51.780
And

183
00:10:52.980 --> 00:10:56.820
this consisted of mailed letters, phone calls, emails, and text

184
00:10:56.880 --> 00:11:00.260
messages to patients reminding them to complete the tests.

185
00:11:01.080 --> 00:11:04.280
Individuals in both arms with an abnormal result received

186
00:11:04.360 --> 00:11:06.160
navigation to colonoscopy.

187
00:11:07.240 --> 00:11:09.300
Next, I'll transition to the results.

188
00:11:10.040 --> 00:11:12.000
This is a little bit of a busy slide.

189
00:11:12.380 --> 00:11:16.100
Forgive me, but this is a description of our study patients

190
00:11:16.140 --> 00:11:18.660
just in the randomized sites in Boston and LA.

191
00:11:18.860 --> 00:11:22.720
I will show you the demographics of the South Dakota site in a second.

192
00:11:23.680 --> 00:11:27.080
We enrolled, as you noticed, just over 5,000 patients.

193
00:11:28.120 --> 00:11:31.840
Overall, the mean age was 55, 59% were

194
00:11:31.940 --> 00:11:35.780
female, 75% were Hispanic or Latino,

195
00:11:36.240 --> 00:11:40.060
7% were non-Hispanic Black, and 15% were non-Hispanic

196
00:11:40.200 --> 00:11:44.190
White. 50% were covered by Medicaid and 12% were

197
00:11:44.240 --> 00:11:47.660
uninsured, with the remainder covered by Medicare or

198
00:11:47.800 --> 00:11:51.780
commercial insurance. Of note, there were more Hispanic

199
00:11:51.880 --> 00:11:55.340
patients in the FIT-DNA arm versus the FIT arm.

200
00:11:55.940 --> 00:11:58.200
And this is shown in the red circles.

201
00:11:58.840 --> 00:12:01.520
There were no differences in insurance.

202
00:12:01.560 --> 00:12:05.020
And although we tried to balance the sites during the

203
00:12:05.060 --> 00:12:08.900
randomization process, this was not totally possible,

204
00:12:08.960 --> 00:12:12.600
and so this demographic difference resulted from differences in the

205
00:12:12.660 --> 00:12:15.280
clinics at the time of randomization.

206
00:12:15.660 --> 00:12:18.860
These are the characteristics of the patients who were enrolled at the

207
00:12:19.120 --> 00:12:22.960
non-randomized tribal site. There, we enrolled just over

208
00:12:22.980 --> 00:12:26.440
800 patients. The mean age was slightly older,

209
00:12:26.860 --> 00:12:30.780
60 years, 56% were female. All of the patients

210
00:12:30.820 --> 00:12:34.460
were American Indian, Alaska Native, and all were covered by the

211
00:12:34.520 --> 00:12:38.384
Indian Health Service.This slide shows

212
00:12:38.604 --> 00:12:42.564
our primary outcome, screening participation within 90 days on

213
00:12:42.624 --> 00:12:45.944
the left. The secondary outcome of participation within

214
00:12:46.104 --> 00:12:49.564
180 days is on the right. For the randomized

215
00:12:49.664 --> 00:12:52.684
clinics, so Boston and LA,

216
00:12:54.604 --> 00:12:58.064
sorry. For the randomized clinics, you can see the comparison of FIT

217
00:12:58.784 --> 00:13:02.604
versus FIT-DNA, and you can see that there was

218
00:13:03.244 --> 00:13:06.484
a significant but modestly, ooh, higher...

219
00:13:06.744 --> 00:13:07.764
I'm not sure what happened here.

220
00:13:12.324 --> 00:13:13.464
It's back.

221
00:13:13.704 --> 00:13:14.484
Okay. All right.

222
00:13:15.444 --> 00:13:16.204
Significant,

223
00:13:17.084 --> 00:13:20.724
but modestly higher return rate in the

224
00:13:20.784 --> 00:13:24.144
FIT-DNA arm compared to the FIT arm,

225
00:13:24.464 --> 00:13:27.864
28% versus 23%. And this difference

226
00:13:28.004 --> 00:13:31.544
persisted at 180 days. Was a little bit

227
00:13:31.624 --> 00:13:34.044
narrower, but still statistically significant.

228
00:13:34.724 --> 00:13:38.564
And you'll notice that in the non-randomized arm, that the return

229
00:13:38.624 --> 00:13:40.264
of FIT-DNA was

230
00:13:41.204 --> 00:13:42.624
also higher.

231
00:13:44.064 --> 00:13:45.984
A little bit lower than in the

232
00:13:47.344 --> 00:13:49.804
randomized site arm. So again,

233
00:13:50.544 --> 00:13:54.504
encouraging that mailed outreach led

234
00:13:54.584 --> 00:13:54.944
to a

235
00:13:56.364 --> 00:13:58.344
significant increase in screening.

236
00:13:59.724 --> 00:14:03.264
This slide shows time to screening in Boston and Los Angeles.

237
00:14:03.864 --> 00:14:07.544
The differences in the two arm became apparent by about 30 days and then

238
00:14:07.664 --> 00:14:10.204
persist through 180 days.

239
00:14:11.564 --> 00:14:15.224
This slide shows differences in screening participation at 90

240
00:14:15.324 --> 00:14:19.104
days for different subgroups. And you'll see that overall

241
00:14:19.244 --> 00:14:22.424
screening completion was higher

242
00:14:23.004 --> 00:14:26.604
in Boston compared to Los Angeles, so

243
00:14:26.804 --> 00:14:28.594
28% versus 23%.

244
00:14:29.424 --> 00:14:33.084
The differences between the FIT and the FIT-DNA

245
00:14:33.184 --> 00:14:36.424
arms were largely driven by Los Angeles, so

246
00:14:36.664 --> 00:14:40.544
28% versus 18% versus

247
00:14:40.964 --> 00:14:42.964
28% and 29%.

248
00:14:43.844 --> 00:14:47.304
And there were no differences at the Boston site.

249
00:14:48.064 --> 00:14:51.304
And we think that this was likely because the Boston sites had a

250
00:14:51.384 --> 00:14:54.484
closer association with an academic health center,

251
00:14:55.684 --> 00:14:59.344
and the clinics in LA had much lower

252
00:14:59.604 --> 00:15:01.844
screening rates at baseline, and so

253
00:15:02.884 --> 00:15:05.644
potential for much greater increase.

254
00:15:06.484 --> 00:15:08.384
The other subgroups that we looked at,

255
00:15:09.204 --> 00:15:11.994
we saw greater use of FIT-DNA among

256
00:15:12.584 --> 00:15:13.944
Hispanic individuals

257
00:15:15.064 --> 00:15:18.004
and those with Medicaid or who were uninsured.

258
00:15:18.324 --> 00:15:21.664
But we think that these differences were likely related to the

259
00:15:21.674 --> 00:15:25.244
differences in the different clinics that persisted

260
00:15:25.284 --> 00:15:26.664
despite randomization.

261
00:15:28.244 --> 00:15:32.204
So I apologize for this being a little bit of a busy slide, but I

262
00:15:32.244 --> 00:15:36.084
will take you through it. The top row shows

263
00:15:36.144 --> 00:15:39.804
the actual screening test that people completed.

264
00:15:39.864 --> 00:15:42.284
So this was a pragmatic randomization.

265
00:15:42.404 --> 00:15:45.774
We reached out to people with the modality that was

266
00:15:45.804 --> 00:15:49.484
selected by the randomization, but the clinics could offer

267
00:15:49.504 --> 00:15:53.464
whatever test they wanted. The clinical team, these were all

268
00:15:53.484 --> 00:15:56.144
people who were due for colorectal cancer screening.

269
00:15:56.204 --> 00:16:00.084
And even though they knew the study was going on, if somebody was sitting

270
00:16:00.104 --> 00:16:03.044
in front of them in their office, they may choose to

271
00:16:04.204 --> 00:16:07.524
screen them on their own. And you'll notice that there is some

272
00:16:07.644 --> 00:16:09.664
crossover in the arms. And so

273
00:16:10.524 --> 00:16:14.444
for people in Boston who were randomized to receive

274
00:16:15.224 --> 00:16:19.124
FIT, there were seven people who received FIT-DNA, so the provider

275
00:16:19.164 --> 00:16:23.084
chose that instead. And for people in the FIT-DNA arm, there were

276
00:16:23.284 --> 00:16:27.184
28 people who received FIT. And I think

277
00:16:27.544 --> 00:16:31.484
FIT has historically been a much more commonly used test in community

278
00:16:31.524 --> 00:16:32.184
health centers.

279
00:16:33.064 --> 00:16:34.084
But recently,

280
00:16:35.144 --> 00:16:38.844
I think largely because of the patient support program provided by the

281
00:16:38.884 --> 00:16:42.284
manufacturer, which takes it out of the hands of the clinic

282
00:16:42.464 --> 00:16:46.384
staff, the clinics have gotten much more comfortable with

283
00:16:46.844 --> 00:16:50.664
offering FIT-DNA. And if you look at the LA

284
00:16:50.744 --> 00:16:54.104
sites, you'll see that there was no crossover between FIT and

285
00:16:54.224 --> 00:16:58.124
FIT-DNA. Those clinics don't offer, and still don't offer actually,

286
00:16:58.224 --> 00:17:01.904
FIT-DNA. And in the FIT-DNA arm, again, some

287
00:17:01.944 --> 00:17:03.264
people who receive FIT

288
00:17:04.384 --> 00:17:08.224
and similar crossover in the South Dakota site with some

289
00:17:08.264 --> 00:17:11.124
people who are receiving FIT-DNA.

290
00:17:12.184 --> 00:17:16.004
And then, I think that what you'll see is we

291
00:17:16.045 --> 00:17:18.565
did a couple of different types of analysis.

292
00:17:19.224 --> 00:17:22.844
The first is that we analyzed them in terms of the abnormal

293
00:17:22.864 --> 00:17:26.075
results per protocol, which meant as

294
00:17:26.144 --> 00:17:29.624
randomized. And you'll see that

295
00:17:30.004 --> 00:17:32.304
this looks at the positivity rate.

296
00:17:32.764 --> 00:17:36.464
There were about 100 people in the randomized clinic who had a positive result,

297
00:17:37.244 --> 00:17:41.084
and there were an additional 26 people in South Dakota

298
00:17:41.864 --> 00:17:43.284
who had a positive result.

299
00:17:44.724 --> 00:17:48.544
And you can see what the positive rates were in these sort of different

300
00:17:48.844 --> 00:17:52.564
buckets. You'll see that South Dakota had a very high

301
00:17:52.584 --> 00:17:56.004
positivity rate, and that is largely

302
00:17:56.124 --> 00:17:59.824
because that population was really pretty

303
00:17:59.884 --> 00:18:03.524
unscreened when we got there. And so this was largely the

304
00:18:03.584 --> 00:18:06.664
first screening test for many of these individuals.

305
00:18:07.404 --> 00:18:11.284
The other thing that you'll see is the positivity rate in Boston is pretty

306
00:18:11.304 --> 00:18:14.384
low. That probably was the most screened group.

307
00:18:14.844 --> 00:18:16.304
And the other thing that you'll notice

308
00:18:17.264 --> 00:18:17.984
is that

309
00:18:18.964 --> 00:18:22.604
there was differences between the brands of FIT kit that were

310
00:18:22.704 --> 00:18:26.524
used. And it's known that there are differences in the quality of FIT

311
00:18:26.564 --> 00:18:30.544
kits that were used. And so one of the things that this

312
00:18:30.784 --> 00:18:34.484
study confirmed is that the Boston sites used a quote, "higher

313
00:18:34.624 --> 00:18:37.944
quality brand of FIT kits" than the LA

314
00:18:38.744 --> 00:18:42.524
clinics. And as a result, that's probably one of the things that

315
00:18:42.604 --> 00:18:46.384
contributed to the higher positivity rate in

316
00:18:46.864 --> 00:18:50.556
Los Angeles.So, unfortunately, colonoscopy

317
00:18:50.596 --> 00:18:53.996
completion after an abnormal test result was limited

318
00:18:54.376 --> 00:18:57.836
despite centralized phone-based navigation by study staff.

319
00:18:58.456 --> 00:19:02.266
Follow-up rate was highest in Boston, which is this

320
00:19:02.316 --> 00:19:02.716
column,

321
00:19:03.816 --> 00:19:07.756
and again, perhaps because of the closer ties

322
00:19:07.776 --> 00:19:11.356
to the academic health center, and it was lowest in

323
00:19:11.456 --> 00:19:14.496
LA because of least access to

324
00:19:14.516 --> 00:19:16.136
colonoscopy in that site.

325
00:19:17.036 --> 00:19:20.656
So, with any study, there are both strengths and limitations.

326
00:19:20.856 --> 00:19:24.656
First, in terms of limitations, this was a pragmatic

327
00:19:24.666 --> 00:19:28.336
trial and the different sites used different FIT kit brands

328
00:19:28.936 --> 00:19:30.896
with different positivity rates.

329
00:19:31.156 --> 00:19:35.065
This is a limitation, but again, pragmatic trial and this is sort of what

330
00:19:35.096 --> 00:19:36.376
you see in real life.

331
00:19:37.276 --> 00:19:41.006
We didn't assess cost effectiveness, which, given the differences in the brands,

332
00:19:41.076 --> 00:19:42.876
might actually be sort of an interesting thing.

333
00:19:43.816 --> 00:19:47.786
And we only tailored our results to English and Spanish languages.

334
00:19:48.186 --> 00:19:51.916
We unfortunately could not randomize the South Dakota site because there

335
00:19:51.976 --> 00:19:55.216
wasn't another site in the region that had

336
00:19:55.276 --> 00:19:58.316
stable enough access to mail

337
00:19:59.196 --> 00:20:02.816
that we could do a mail population outreach intervention.

338
00:20:03.716 --> 00:20:07.616
In terms of the strengths, we conducted a pragmatic

339
00:20:07.736 --> 00:20:11.716
study design with a large sample. The study was implemented in

340
00:20:11.756 --> 00:20:15.436
multiple regions with different population subgroups and

341
00:20:15.496 --> 00:20:19.036
community health centers. We also focused on an

342
00:20:19.096 --> 00:20:21.256
under-resourced community setting

343
00:20:22.356 --> 00:20:25.396
and this is increasingly an important source of

344
00:20:25.436 --> 00:20:28.776
healthcare in this country that is unfortunately often

345
00:20:28.916 --> 00:20:30.376
overlooked in research.

346
00:20:31.216 --> 00:20:34.816
And finally, the study fostered academic and community

347
00:20:34.956 --> 00:20:38.796
partnerships that are going to continue and are going to be

348
00:20:38.856 --> 00:20:42.276
leveraged for hopefully some new opportunities.

349
00:20:42.356 --> 00:20:46.036
So, in conclusion, in terms of the study, the CARE study

350
00:20:46.096 --> 00:20:49.876
showed that CRC screening uptake was modestly higher in the

351
00:20:49.936 --> 00:20:53.656
FIT-DNA arm than in the FIT arm, but that the majority of

352
00:20:53.716 --> 00:20:56.136
individuals in both arms remained

353
00:20:56.276 --> 00:21:00.116
unscreened. And we saw regional differences in

354
00:21:00.176 --> 00:21:03.516
uptake and positivity, likely driven by

355
00:21:03.656 --> 00:21:07.536
access to both prior screening as well as colonoscopy and

356
00:21:07.556 --> 00:21:08.116
FIT brand.

357
00:21:09.296 --> 00:21:13.036
Colonoscopy follow-up was suboptimal at all of the sites, despite

358
00:21:13.096 --> 00:21:16.956
navigation. And the CARE study really serves

359
00:21:16.996 --> 00:21:20.876
as an early demonstration of how to implement mailed FIT and

360
00:21:20.936 --> 00:21:23.226
FIT-DNA in underserved settings.

361
00:21:23.806 --> 00:21:27.366
So, there was actually an additional aim in our grant, and it

362
00:21:27.476 --> 00:21:31.416
is the best aim of the grant, and I think

363
00:21:31.476 --> 00:21:34.705
that it was really the best part of this award,

364
00:21:35.516 --> 00:21:37.496
that it included a mentorship aim.

