was truly eligible. This is basically due to the difference in

762
00:43:50.564 --> 00:43:54.104
comorbidity loads that minority patients tend to have.

763
00:43:55.094 --> 00:43:58.244
And once you actually were eligible, no racial

764
00:43:58.304 --> 00:44:01.724
difference in actual enrollment in a clinical trial.

765
00:44:03.084 --> 00:44:06.884
So this just gives you a sense of what we actually

766
00:44:07.004 --> 00:44:10.544
went through in terms of identifying patients at treatment decision

767
00:44:10.584 --> 00:44:14.564
points. And so this is just one of the institutions, and you can

768
00:44:14.664 --> 00:44:18.584
see of patients who are identified at a treatment decision

769
00:44:18.624 --> 00:44:22.004
point, if you're new, clearly you have to have a different treatment.

770
00:44:22.064 --> 00:44:23.504
You have to have some treatment started.

771
00:44:23.853 --> 00:44:27.784
If you're an established patient, you have to have a scan to determine whether or

772
00:44:27.844 --> 00:44:29.304
not you have disease progression.

773
00:44:30.224 --> 00:44:33.364
The algorithm was actually pretty good at being able to

774
00:44:33.404 --> 00:44:36.544
identify people who had negative scans, who

775
00:44:37.284 --> 00:44:39.464
are not eligible for trials at that point,

776
00:44:40.584 --> 00:44:44.524
and don't need to be manually reviewed to see if anything else has to

777
00:44:44.564 --> 00:44:44.964
happen.

778
00:44:45.874 --> 00:44:49.783
Not so good with the positive scans or the mixed scans.

779
00:44:49.804 --> 00:44:53.304
But the bottom line about the algorithm is at least this actually

780
00:44:53.524 --> 00:44:56.704
reduced manual review by

781
00:44:56.884 --> 00:45:00.844
35%. So still, a significant time saving in trying

782
00:45:00.884 --> 00:45:02.144
to identify patients.

783
00:45:03.184 --> 00:45:06.944
The algorithms work variably on being able to actually

784
00:45:06.984 --> 00:45:10.924
stage the patients because we needed that, obviously, and biomarker

785
00:45:11.344 --> 00:45:14.844
receptor status in order to be able to match them to appropriate

786
00:45:14.854 --> 00:45:15.484
trials.

787
00:45:16.404 --> 00:45:19.664
And you see, there's variability.

788
00:45:19.744 --> 00:45:22.364
And our biggest challenge with this is timing.

789
00:45:23.184 --> 00:45:27.044
So for example, for lung cancer patients, they would come in in the morning

790
00:45:27.064 --> 00:45:28.044
and get a scan.

791
00:45:29.464 --> 00:45:33.364
We didn't have the results of that scan in the EMR to be able to even

792
00:45:33.464 --> 00:45:37.384
run an algorithm on it by the time they saw their physician in the

793
00:45:37.484 --> 00:45:38.104
afternoon.

794
00:45:39.064 --> 00:45:43.034
When we did, on the retrospective sample, use these same algorithms,

795
00:45:43.264 --> 00:45:46.804
actually, the accuracy for staging goes up to over

796
00:45:47.044 --> 00:45:50.924
90%. So this, we still are working on this piece.

797
00:45:51.704 --> 00:45:55.584
And then just to give a sense of sort of that funnel

798
00:45:55.724 --> 00:45:59.324
of all the folks who are coming in. So out of more than

799
00:45:59.644 --> 00:46:02.564
70,000 patients, our IT

800
00:46:03.444 --> 00:46:07.364
identified folks at a treatment decision point of a little less

801
00:46:07.404 --> 00:46:10.904
than 14,000. But refining the

802
00:46:10.984 --> 00:46:13.504
algorithms brought it down much further.

803
00:46:14.584 --> 00:46:16.444
Then we were able to consent patients.

804
00:46:16.784 --> 00:46:19.944
I will say that we had a much higher refusal rate than we

805
00:46:19.984 --> 00:46:23.184
expected, and most of that was due to the fact

806
00:46:23.284 --> 00:46:27.044
that it's an extremely emotional time for people,

807
00:46:27.684 --> 00:46:30.984
and they just did not want to deal with research, period.

808
00:46:32.364 --> 00:46:36.344
But once we actually did get folks consented, you can see that of those

809
00:46:36.364 --> 00:46:39.984
who actually were eligible for trials, we were able to

810
00:46:40.044 --> 00:46:43.884
enroll 27%. And to put that into perspective, at the

811
00:46:43.984 --> 00:46:47.464
NCI centers, it was a little less than

812
00:46:47.624 --> 00:46:50.024
22%. So it looks like we're doing pretty well.

813
00:46:51.684 --> 00:46:54.404
So what did we learn from the oncologist?

814
00:46:54.984 --> 00:46:58.884
We actually had a 97% participation rate

815
00:46:58.944 --> 00:47:00.804
of all the oncologists taken care of.

816
00:47:02.004 --> 00:47:05.724
This was focused on breast, lung, and liver cancer patients.

817
00:47:06.544 --> 00:47:09.804
And we got 100% response rate from all of them on the survey.

818
00:47:10.964 --> 00:47:14.824
But the biggest things that really would interfere with, from their perspective of

819
00:47:14.844 --> 00:47:18.324
who they'd offer trials to, were patients who had family

820
00:47:18.364 --> 00:47:21.524
responsibilities and work time constraints.

821
00:47:22.224 --> 00:47:24.364
Which is really important because

822
00:47:25.624 --> 00:47:26.824
when we talk to patients,

823
00:47:27.784 --> 00:47:31.464
you can see that family responsibilities were actually much more

824
00:47:31.524 --> 00:47:35.224
common among our Black patients as compared to white

825
00:47:35.284 --> 00:47:37.624
patients and other access barriers.

826
00:47:38.224 --> 00:47:38.484
So,

827
00:47:39.784 --> 00:47:41.344
the likelihood of being offered

828
00:47:43.124 --> 00:47:44.224
a clinical trial

829
00:47:45.204 --> 00:47:49.084
seems likely to be less for minority patients.

830
00:47:50.644 --> 00:47:52.544
In fact, when you look at what

831
00:47:53.444 --> 00:47:57.044
patients' attitudes are towards clinical trials, they're actually pretty

832
00:47:57.084 --> 00:47:57.684
positive.

833
00:47:58.554 --> 00:48:00.433
We didn't make that much of a difference

834
00:48:01.244 --> 00:48:02.803
with the education that we did.

835
00:48:03.803 --> 00:48:07.024
Blacks, it got a little bit better, but it's not statistically significant.

836
00:48:07.384 --> 00:48:11.224
But the bottom line about this is there were no racial ethnic differences

837
00:48:11.304 --> 00:48:15.224
in patients' positive attitudes about clinical trials.

838
00:48:15.244 --> 00:48:19.044
And there was also no racial ethnic difference in patient report of the

839
00:48:19.104 --> 00:48:21.364
doc talking to them about clinical trials.

840
00:48:25.184 --> 00:48:25.504
Oops.

841
00:48:26.784 --> 00:48:30.464
All right. Our third aim was focused on disrupting the

842
00:48:30.524 --> 00:48:32.004
research and education

843
00:48:33.564 --> 00:48:34.624
approaches. And

844
00:48:35.684 --> 00:48:39.504
what we did towards that end was we actually funded

845
00:48:39.544 --> 00:48:42.224
pilot studies that were focused on

846
00:48:42.244 --> 00:48:46.224
disparities. And we required that

847
00:48:46.284 --> 00:48:50.244
each of these studies must have a community scientist because we

848
00:48:50.304 --> 00:48:54.294
really wanted to stimulate research that was relevant to

849
00:48:54.324 --> 00:48:57.884
the communities. What we learned in that process

850
00:48:58.184 --> 00:49:01.854
was we actually needed to do some work to train community

851
00:49:01.944 --> 00:49:05.844
members who were interested to be able to be active participants in

852
00:49:05.904 --> 00:49:09.634
this. And so we created a community scientist institute,

853
00:49:10.644 --> 00:49:14.254
which is now a certificate-granting program at the City College of New York.

854
00:49:14.804 --> 00:49:18.104
And the CSI has already graduated 26

855
00:49:18.144 --> 00:49:21.824
individuals who have been participating, not just in the pilot

856
00:49:21.884 --> 00:49:25.784
studies that we funded, but actually in additional research

857
00:49:26.864 --> 00:49:29.464
proposals that have gone into the NIH.

858
00:49:30.724 --> 00:49:34.384
In addition to that, and Jen talked about the importance of

859
00:49:34.444 --> 00:49:37.484
mentoring, we wanted to bring a lot of the

860
00:49:37.664 --> 00:49:41.604
experiences and exposures to community and working with

861
00:49:41.684 --> 00:49:45.104
community to really embed that in the next

862
00:49:45.204 --> 00:49:48.704
generation. And so we created a student health ambassador

863
00:49:48.844 --> 00:49:52.774
program. So we involve students. We had folks from

864
00:49:52.804 --> 00:49:55.574
York College, from NYU, from City

865
00:49:55.724 --> 00:49:59.500
College.Joining in in the

866
00:49:59.540 --> 00:50:03.420
different community-involved events, learning how to be able to

867
00:50:03.480 --> 00:50:06.250
work with community and how to talk with community.

868
00:50:07.480 --> 00:50:10.900
So far, we've trained 14 students who work closely.

869
00:50:10.940 --> 00:50:14.690
This was from one of the important synergies between Aims

870
00:50:14.980 --> 00:50:18.880
3 and Aim 1. And we also taught a health equity course to basic

871
00:50:18.940 --> 00:50:21.020
scientists and to medical students.

872
00:50:23.740 --> 00:50:27.140
What did we learn? Well, we've learned a lot of things.

873
00:50:28.480 --> 00:50:32.400
We found that working with community organizations is critical

874
00:50:32.980 --> 00:50:36.060
to build trust, to really focus on

875
00:50:36.340 --> 00:50:39.460
collaborations, and work through a lot of the issues,

876
00:50:39.960 --> 00:50:43.220
particularly as we moved into

877
00:50:44.180 --> 00:50:47.340
how you go about really creating

878
00:50:47.860 --> 00:50:50.880
expectations around deliverables and finance,

879
00:50:51.720 --> 00:50:53.720
and really working through those actual

880
00:50:53.760 --> 00:50:57.530
negotiations. The other key piece about

881
00:50:57.620 --> 00:50:58.570
this is that

882
00:51:00.340 --> 00:51:04.330
as we work through all that, but resources are critical

883
00:51:04.860 --> 00:51:08.400
for this kind of work to happen, and really being able to

884
00:51:08.460 --> 00:51:12.440
find ongoing resources for community to continue this kind of work

885
00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:15.620
is critical and remains a challenge.

886
00:51:16.780 --> 00:51:20.660
We learned that community members are interested in getting trained about clinical

887
00:51:20.670 --> 00:51:24.100
research and to become community scientists.

888
00:51:24.110 --> 00:51:27.920
We learned that the majority of patients are actually open to the idea

889
00:51:27.980 --> 00:51:31.360
of clinical trials, and that there was not a racial ethnic

890
00:51:31.400 --> 00:51:35.320
disparity in attitudes towards clinical research and clinical

891
00:51:35.360 --> 00:51:38.920
trials. And we also found that we did not see

892
00:51:39.860 --> 00:51:41.380
a racial ethnic difference in

893
00:51:42.460 --> 00:51:45.320
who the docs talked to about clinical trials.

894
00:51:46.420 --> 00:51:50.320
We found, as many have, and is well known, that minority patients

895
00:51:50.360 --> 00:51:52.920
are less likely to be eligible for clinical trials.

896
00:51:54.660 --> 00:51:58.620
And we also found that it's possible to match trials to patients

897
00:51:58.640 --> 00:52:00.860
and not just patients to trials.

898
00:52:01.860 --> 00:52:05.280
We found that timing is critical. Timing is critical for

899
00:52:05.460 --> 00:52:07.900
algorithm accuracy, and

900
00:52:09.160 --> 00:52:11.690
it's also critical for patients'

901
00:52:11.760 --> 00:52:15.720
abilities to even hear about the possibility

902
00:52:15.760 --> 00:52:19.640
of participating in research, even when they may be open to

903
00:52:19.740 --> 00:52:21.340
it, to the idea of it.

904
00:52:22.620 --> 00:52:26.560
That's really important when you think about interventions that we would need to

905
00:52:26.600 --> 00:52:30.220
do moving forward, because this is not a knowledge

906
00:52:30.320 --> 00:52:33.500
issue. This is an emotional issue.

907
00:52:33.540 --> 00:52:37.280
And so educating about clinical trials is really not going to help solve that

908
00:52:37.320 --> 00:52:37.860
challenge.

909
00:52:39.660 --> 00:52:43.040
We learned a lot about text messaging because we wanted to do text

910
00:52:43.080 --> 00:52:46.980
messaging to get at the population that wasn't enrolled in MyChart,

911
00:52:47.400 --> 00:52:49.420
which is part of the patient portal for Epic.

912
00:52:50.460 --> 00:52:53.780
There were actually a lot of problems with that, starting with wrong telephone

913
00:52:53.840 --> 00:52:57.740
numbers and some of the structures within Epic that made that essentially

914
00:52:57.800 --> 00:52:58.449
impossible.

915
00:52:59.420 --> 00:52:59.890
And then,

916
00:53:00.840 --> 00:53:04.620
the big problem, which everybody knows about, is there's a

917
00:53:04.700 --> 00:53:08.560
huge mismatch between the kinds of trials that are

918
00:53:08.680 --> 00:53:12.040
open and available to patients and what the patient's clinical

919
00:53:12.140 --> 00:53:15.720
characteristics are. So we had a lot more early-stage

920
00:53:15.820 --> 00:53:19.320
patients than we had trials available for early-stage patients.

921
00:53:19.940 --> 00:53:23.610
And to get at that, we tried. We had a networking

922
00:53:23.660 --> 00:53:27.520
event where we actually invited pharma along with a whole bunch of the

923
00:53:27.560 --> 00:53:31.380
researchers, both basic and translational, and patients in community.

924
00:53:31.940 --> 00:53:35.620
And I got to say, pharma got quite an earful from community

925
00:53:36.100 --> 00:53:36.660
about

926
00:53:37.720 --> 00:53:41.680
the need to open up trials, and potential ways of doing this

927
00:53:41.760 --> 00:53:45.400
were really discussed in the different work groups, but it really has a long way to

928
00:53:45.480 --> 00:53:45.699
go.

929
00:53:47.720 --> 00:53:51.300
And I just want to end by thanking our

930
00:53:51.380 --> 00:53:52.220
incredible

931
00:53:53.240 --> 00:53:56.580
community partners, our clinical partners, our

932
00:53:56.620 --> 00:53:59.240
educational partners. This really has been

933
00:54:00.560 --> 00:54:03.720
a project filled with incredible devotion,

934
00:54:04.740 --> 00:54:08.680
love, work. And so many people made this possible

935
00:54:09.480 --> 00:54:13.360
because all of them were needed. This is the community

936
00:54:13.460 --> 00:54:16.829
out in the communities, but the clinical communities,

937
00:54:18.400 --> 00:54:20.220
people were really open and

938
00:54:21.740 --> 00:54:25.100
really open to participating and really trying to change the

939
00:54:25.160 --> 00:54:27.720
system. So I just wanted to acknowledge that.

940
00:54:30.300 --> 00:54:30.700
Thank you.

941
00:54:32.700 --> 00:54:34.200
Any

942
00:54:36.340 --> 00:54:36.630
questions?

943
00:54:36.630 --> 00:54:39.970
Questions from the floor. I see Bill coming up. Great.

944
00:54:41.420 --> 00:54:44.620
So the tool you developed to screen for

945
00:54:45.820 --> 00:54:48.360
what kind of people would participate in what kind of trial seems

946
00:54:49.560 --> 00:54:51.840
especially helpful in the scheme of things.

947
00:54:51.900 --> 00:54:53.910
If you look at our nation's cancer centers,

948
00:54:54.840 --> 00:54:58.820
Rob's looking at me. I'm like, the EAB of 25% of them or something at this

949
00:54:58.860 --> 00:55:02.540
point. One of the things they are supposed to do when they think of

950
00:55:02.580 --> 00:55:06.260
launching a clinical trial with the help of one of our pharma friends or not,

951
00:55:06.760 --> 00:55:10.180
is they're supposed to prospectively say, "This is the number of people we are

952
00:55:10.190 --> 00:55:12.860
likely to see who would be eligible and we're going to accrue."

953
00:55:13.140 --> 00:55:13.210
Mm-hmm.

954
00:55:13.300 --> 00:55:17.240
And yet, I can tell you that this is one of the biggest stumbling blocks at most

955
00:55:17.320 --> 00:55:20.940
of our country's cancer centers. They do the wrong trials for the wrong people.

956
00:55:20.970 --> 00:55:20.990
Mm-hmm.

957
00:55:21.000 --> 00:55:24.360
Oftentimes, they do stupid trials, which is a different issue altogether that you

958
00:55:24.380 --> 00:55:27.220
don't have to deal with. But they definitely do the wrong trials for the wrong

959
00:55:27.280 --> 00:55:30.800
people. They don't launch trials for the people that they're

960
00:55:30.920 --> 00:55:31.660
actually seeing.

961
00:55:32.460 --> 00:55:35.740
Your tool should not have been a surprise to them, but it's a good tool.

962
00:55:35.800 --> 00:55:39.580
What I was wondering, have you thought about using it prospectively along with the

963
00:55:39.620 --> 00:55:42.840
people as they begin to launch the trials or with IRB approval or something?

964
00:55:44.080 --> 00:55:45.800
Well, this was all prospective.

965
00:55:47.160 --> 00:55:48.220
Just FYI, but...

966
00:55:48.480 --> 00:55:51.460
No, I mean prospectively to the people who haven't yet proposed a trial.

967
00:55:51.540 --> 00:55:52.960
Say, "Look, this is who you're seeing."

968
00:55:53.520 --> 00:55:53.800
Yeah.

969
00:55:53.960 --> 00:55:54.100
Yeah.

970
00:55:54.540 --> 00:55:58.440
So we've been working closely with our cancer center director, trying to

971
00:55:58.460 --> 00:56:01.180
figure out how we can now really...

972
00:56:01.560 --> 00:56:03.790
Because we've built all the infrastructure,

973
00:56:04.600 --> 00:56:05.420
so how can

974
00:56:06.460 --> 00:56:09.240
we embed this so that they can use it?

975
00:56:10.780 --> 00:56:12.820
Because it's there for them to use.

976
00:56:12.980 --> 00:56:15.600
So it is a work in progress.

977
00:56:18.010 --> 00:56:20.910
Yeah. Thank you. Marie-Pierre St-Laurent from Vancouver in Canada.

978
00:56:21.410 --> 00:56:25.190
I do research. I'm a physician, and trying to see what

979
00:56:25.310 --> 00:56:27.860
can be used about what you presented. It's quite interesting.

980
00:56:28.170 --> 00:56:31.490
A few technical questions. The tool you've talked about in the first part,

981
00:56:32.110 --> 00:56:35.770
how long before the appointment with the physician will that education take place?

982
00:56:35.830 --> 00:56:39.700
Just in terms of making it for the patients, kind of integrating and

983
00:56:39.730 --> 00:56:40.789
not being overwhelming.

984
00:56:41.730 --> 00:56:45.450
Is that potential ways of educating the patients to research

985
00:56:45.490 --> 00:56:46.570
available in a way?

986
00:56:47.870 --> 00:56:48.110
So,

987
00:56:50.149 --> 00:56:51.210
happy to make it available.

988
00:56:52.310 --> 00:56:56.270
The way that we ended up figuring out how to do this

989
00:56:56.390 --> 00:57:00.030
was... And the reason I'm not giving you a straight answer is because it varied.

990
00:57:02.430 --> 00:57:06.290
What we aimed to do was first we

991
00:57:06.310 --> 00:57:09.790
talked to all the docs and a bunch of the

992
00:57:10.130 --> 00:57:14.030
nurses, management, front desk, everybody, to get a sense of, as

993
00:57:14.070 --> 00:57:17.110
Jim was talking about, workflows and

994
00:57:17.670 --> 00:57:21.530
timing, and when did they want to get this kind of information and

995
00:57:21.610 --> 00:57:22.049
how.

996
00:57:23.570 --> 00:57:26.280
So the ideal was, and the

997
00:57:26.410 --> 00:57:29.590
compromise was that we would

998
00:57:30.010 --> 00:57:31.050
identify

999
00:57:33.150 --> 00:57:37.010
patients at that first visit when they were either a new patient or

1000
00:57:37.050 --> 00:57:39.750
had evidence of disease progression.

1001
00:57:39.850 --> 00:57:41.800
And we would consent them,

1002
00:57:43.150 --> 00:57:47.010
at that time and feedback information prior to the

1003
00:57:47.150 --> 00:57:50.810
next visit, the second visit, because theoretically,

1004
00:57:51.250 --> 00:57:55.030
that first visit was to talk about the cancer for new

1005
00:57:55.070 --> 00:57:55.530
patients,

1006
00:57:56.410 --> 00:58:00.290
and potential treatments. And the second one was going to be to talk about

1007
00:58:00.370 --> 00:58:03.830
actual treatments and make the decisions what would happen.

1008
00:58:05.170 --> 00:58:08.750
What ended up happening is that, in fact, most of the

1009
00:58:08.790 --> 00:58:11.190
decisions were being made at that first visit.

1010
00:58:12.230 --> 00:58:15.790
So we needed to get this information to the docs and the

1011
00:58:15.830 --> 00:58:16.490
patients,

1012
00:58:17.350 --> 00:58:19.210
even before they saw the docs.

